Executive Summary

The goal of this project is to build a predictive text mining application. The project progresses step wise starting with loading the text documents, exploring content and characteristics of the text. The next step involves consolidating the given text documents, cleaning up the content and building up a clean corpus for text processing using R’s natural language processing packages. The next step entails analysing the corpus in terms of n-grams. The next step will involve building a basic n-gram model for predicting the next word based on the previous 1, 2, or 3 words. Further steps will refine the n-gram based predictive model to become more robust in handling more complex corpus.

It is clear from the file sizes and Word statistics review that our selected files are too big for analysis with file disk and memory constraints.Therefore need to sample the data. In this case I have sampled 0.2% of each of the text files.

set.seed(9) # Make subsampling reproducible
sample_size <- 0.002 # Subsample to 0.2%
sampleBlogs <- blogs[sample(1:length(blogs),length(blogs)*sample_size)]
sampleNews <- news[sample(1:length(news),length(news)*sample_size)]
sampleTwitters <- twitters[sample(1:length(twitters),length(twitters)*sample_size)]
writeLines(c(sampleBlogs,sampleNews,sampleTwitters), "sampleCombinedText.txt")

Task3:Data Cleaning and building a Corpus.

This task involves removing non-text characters and punctuation marks and converting capital letters to case and building a corpus.

library(tm) ##Load Text Mining library
## Loading required package: NLP
## 
## Attaching package: 'NLP'
## The following object is masked from 'package:ggplot2':
## 
##     annotate
combinedRoughSample <- readLines("sampleCombinedText.txt")
corpusRoughSample <- Corpus(VectorSource(combinedRoughSample))

toSpace <- content_transformer(function(x, pattern) gsub(pattern, " ", x))
corpusRoughSample<- tm_map(corpusRoughSample,toSpace,"/|@|\\|")
corpusRoughSample <- tm_map(corpusRoughSample,content_transformer(tolower))
corpusRoughSample <- tm_map(corpusRoughSample,removeNumbers)
corpusRoughSample <- tm_map(corpusRoughSample,removePunctuation)
CorpusClean <- tm_map(corpusRoughSample,stripWhitespace)
saveRDS(CorpusClean, 
        file = "final/finalCorpus.RDS")

finalCorpus <- readRDS("final/finalCorpus.RDS")

finalCorpusDF <-data.frame(text=unlist(sapply(finalCorpus,
                                              `[`, "content")), 
                           stringsAsFactors = FALSE)

Task 4: Analyzing the sample corpus text dump

The corpus is analyzed using wordcloud graphic and n-grams histograms.

nGrams <- function(corpDF, grams) {
  ngram <- NGramTokenizer(corpDF, Weka_control(min = grams, max = grams,
                      delimiters = " \\r\\n\\t.,;:\"()?!"))
  ngram <- data.frame(table(ngram))
  ngram <- ngram[order(ngram$Freq,decreasing = TRUE),]
  colnames(ngram) <- c("String","Count")
  return(ngram)
}

unigram <- nGrams(finalCorpusDF, 1)
bigram <- nGrams(finalCorpusDF, 2)

fourgram <- nGrams(finalCorpusDF, 4)

Findings and next steps

The downloaded text documents are quite huge with over 60 million words. Thus sampling with even 0.5% of takes too long time to carryout analysis. Possibly explore using even smaller sample.

Explore more efficient analytic functions that do not consume high processing resources

Apparently with the some of the text contains foreign language (other than English) words.

Possibly refine the corpus even more

The n-gram modelling seems like a plausible strategy to base the text predictive model.Need to refine n-gram results for example sort by most frequent word phrases.

Next steps is to refine sampling and develop the the basic text predictive model based on the n-grams and progressively improve it.
